        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "You need a casserole dish with a tight-fitting lid, large enough to hold everything in a snug single layer. A 28 cm cast-iron casserole is ideal.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Brown the beef",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Heat the oven to 160°C conventional. Pat the beef dry with kitchen paper and season well with salt and pepper.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Warm the oil in the casserole dish over a high heat. Brown the beef in two or three batches, turning each piece so all sides are deep brown, about 3 minutes per batch. Lift out and set aside.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Build the base",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Reduce the heat to medium. Add the onion to the same casserole and cook for 5 minutes until softened. Add the flour and stir for 1 minute until it coats the onion.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Add the tomato puree and cook for 1 minute, then pour in the stock, ",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": []
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "deglazing",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmp73vlkc0001wwv4i1qpucp8"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " the base as you stir. Add the Worcestershire sauce, bay leaves, and thyme sprigs.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Return the beef to the casserole along with the carrot and parsnip. The liquid should come about two-thirds up the sides of the meat. Add a splash more stock or water if not.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Slow-braise and finish",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Cover with the lid and transfer to the oven. Cook for 2 to 2.5 hours until the beef is tender enough to break apart with a spoon. Check after 1.5 hours and add a little water if it looks dry.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Remove the bay leaves and thyme stalks. Taste and adjust the seasoning. Serve with mashed potato, crusty bread, or rice.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Lift out the beef and vegetables and simmer the gravy uncovered on the hob for 10 minutes until it thickens. Return everything to the pot.",
                "cause": "The lid was left off, or the heat was too low to reduce the liquid.",
                "symptom": "The gravy is thin"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Return to the oven, covered, for another 30 to 45 minutes and test again.",
                "cause": "Chuck needs time. It can take up to 3 hours depending on how cold it was when it went in.",
                "symptom": "The beef is tough after 2 hours"
              },
              {
                "fix": "This cannot be undone during cooking, but add a teaspoon of marmite stirred in at the end to deepen the colour and flavour.",
                "cause": "The beef was not browned enough at the start.",
                "symptom": "The stew looks pale and tastes flat"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Cut them no smaller than 3 cm for a 2.5-hour braise. If they are already soft, serve immediately; they will hold their shape less well on reheating.",
                "cause": "The root vegetables were cut too small, or the braise ran too long.",
                "symptom": "The vegetables are falling apart"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Brown stew sits at the heart of British farmhouse cooking, a dish of frugal good sense: cheaper cuts of meat, whatever root vegetables were to hand, and a slow oven. It has no precise origin and no single recipe; every household had a version. What unites them is the dark, sticky gravy and the patience required to get there.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
